            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I ran into this while working on a feature for zls and bisected to:\n\n```gitcommit\nb87505e11656163ddf0dbbc16b7d224815873964 is the first bad commit\ncommit b87505e11656163ddf0dbbc16b7d224815873964\nAuthor: Lewis Russell <lewis6991@gmail.com>\nDate:   Wed Feb 7 11:24:44 2024 +0000\n\n    refactor(watch): general tidy up\n\n    - Rename watch.poll to watch.watchdirs\n    - Unify how include and exclude is applied\n    - Improve type hints\n\n runtime/lua/vim/_watch.lua          | 202 ++++++++++++++++++++++---------------------\n runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_watchfiles.lua |   7 +-\n test/functional/lua/watch_spec.lua  | 218 +++++++++++++++++------------------------------\n test/functional/plugin/lsp_spec.lua | 194 ++++++++++++++++++++++-------------------\n test/helpers.lua                    |  51 +++++------\n 5 files changed, 319 insertions(+), 353 deletions(-)\n```\n\nBefore [this](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/commit/b87505e11656163ddf0dbbc16b7d224815873964) commit, watchers were created as long as their path didn't match the exclude pattern. After, they had to match the include pattern (via `skip`). I believe the issue is that parent directories containing a path that should match won't match by themselves. For example:\n\n- path: `src/foo/bar.txt`\n- include_pattern `**/*.txt`\n\nIn this loop:\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/2d11b981bfbb7816d88a69b43b758f3a3f515b96/runtime/lua/vim/_watch.lua#L219-L228\n\nif path is say, `src/foo`, this *won't* match `include_pattern`, so a watch won't end up being made even though files inside of `src/foo` should be watched. A simple fix would be to check if a path isn't excluded in this loop again, but I'm not sure if that would introduce different regressions.",
